AD  - Chungbuk National University, Department of Chemical Engineering, Cheongju, Chungcheongbuk-do, South Korea
AB  - The gut microbiota plays a pivotal role in metabolic health, influencing processes ranging from energy homeostasis to immune function. Nicotinamide mononucleotide (NMN), a key precursor of NAD+, has emerged as a promising therapeutic agent for metabolic disorders and aging. Recent evidence suggests a dynamic interplay between NMN and the gut microbiota, with NMN influencing microbial composition and diversity, while the microbiota modulates NMN metabolism and bioavailability. This review explores the bidirectional relationship between NMN and the microbiota, highlighting their collective impact on metabolic health. Furthermore, we discuss therapeutic strategies leveraging this interplay, such as combined NMN-probiotic interventions, and outline future directions for research and clinical applications. © 2026 Taylor & Francis Group, LLC.
